abindex="-1" dir="auto" data-turn-id="1dd36708-b0ee-48dd-ab20-e712d534a0e1" data-testid="conversation-turn-2" data-scroll-anchor="false" data-turn="assistant"><h6 class="sr-only">ChatGPT said:</h6><div class="text-base my-auto mx-auto [--thread-content-margin:--spacing(4)] @w-sm/main:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(6)] @w-lg/main:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(16)] px-(--thread-content-margin)"><div class="[--thread-content-max-width:40rem] @w-lg/main:[--thread-content-max-width:48rem] mx-auto max-w-(--thread-content-max-width) flex-1 group/turn-messages focus-visible:outline-hidden relative flex w-full min-w-0 flex-col agent-turn" tabindex="-1"><div class="flex max-w-full flex-col grow"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="8a574514-85d0-4f11-ac2b-605990368b75" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1" data-message-model-slug="gpt-5-2"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="262">Here’s a <strong data-start="9" data-end="42">clean synthesis and deepening</strong> of what Kempes is doing conceptually, followed by a <strong data-start="95" data-end="161">focused expansion on the error threshold and ontogenic hacking</strong>, framed in a way that aligns with universal, substrate-independent theory rather than Earth biology.</p>
<hr data-start="264" data-end="267">
<h2 data-start="269" data-end="315">1. What Kempes Is Really After (Compressed)</h2>
<p data-start="317" data-end="526">In this interview, <strong data-start="336" data-end="377"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Chris Kempes</span></span></strong> (of the <strong data-start="386" data-end="427"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Santa Fe Institute</span></span></strong>) is not proposing <em data-start="446" data-end="474">another definition of life</em>. He is proposing a <strong data-start="494" data-end="516">compression scheme</strong> for life.</p>
<p data-start="528" data-end="550">The core move is this:</p>
<blockquote data-start="552" data-end="707">
<p data-start="554" data-end="707"><strong data-start="554" data-end="707">Life should be understood as a scale-bridging, information-bearing optimization process constrained by physics but independent of material substrate.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p data-start="709" data-end="761">Everything else in the interview supports that move.</p>
<hr data-start="763" data-end="766">
<h2 data-start="768" data-end="832">2. The “Three Cultures” as a Navigation Tool (Not a Taxonomy)</h2>
<p data-start="834" data-end="943">The triangle Kempes describes is not a classification of scientists—it’s a <strong data-start="909" data-end="942">methodological control system</strong>.</p>
<ul data-start="945" data-end="1130">
<li data-start="945" data-end="1006">
<p data-start="947" data-end="1006"><strong data-start="947" data-end="967">Variance culture</strong> guards against premature abstraction</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1007" data-end="1060">
<p data-start="1009" data-end="1060"><strong data-start="1009" data-end="1031">Exactitude culture</strong> guards against hand-waving</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1061" data-end="1130">
<p data-start="1063" data-end="1130"><strong data-start="1063" data-end="1093">Coarse-grained abstraction</strong> guards against drowning in details</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1132" data-end="1246">“Walking the corners” is essentially a <strong data-start="1171" data-end="1199">renormalization workflow</strong>:<br data-start="1200" data-end="1203">
you zoom in → simulate → compress → repeat.</p>
<p data-start="1248" data-end="1350">This already places his work closer to statistical physics and information theory than biology proper.</p>
<hr data-start="1352" data-end="1355">
<h2 data-start="1357" data-end="1413">3. The Universal Hierarchy Is a Factorization of Life</h2>
<p data-start="1415" data-end="1510">The Optimization / Constraints / Materials hierarchy is best understood as a <strong data-start="1492" data-end="1509">factorization</strong>:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Life</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>Optimization&nbsp;Dynamics</mtext><mtext>  </mtext><mo>∘</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mtext>Physical&nbsp;Constraints</mtext><mtext>  </mtext><mo>∘</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mtext>Material&nbsp;Substrate</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{Life} = \text{Optimization Dynamics} \;\circ\; \text{Physical Constraints} \;\circ\; \text{Material Substrate}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Life</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8778em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Optimization&nbsp;Dynamics</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span><span class="mbin">∘</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Physical&nbsp;Constraints</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span><span class="mbin">∘</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Material&nbsp;Substrate</span></span></span></span></span></span>
<h3 data-start="1636" data-end="1656">Why this matters</h3>
<ul data-start="1657" data-end="1828">
<li data-start="1657" data-end="1702">
<p data-start="1659" data-end="1702">It <strong data-start="1662" data-end="1702">separates contingency from necessity</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1703" data-end="1759">
<p data-start="1705" data-end="1759">It explains <strong data-start="1717" data-end="1741">convergent evolution</strong> without mysticism</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1760" data-end="1828">
<p data-start="1762" data-end="1828">It allows <strong data-start="1772" data-end="1795">non-biological life</strong> to be discussed without metaphor</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1830" data-end="1861">DNA is not special. Physics is.</p>
<hr data-start="1863" data-end="1866">
<h2 data-start="1868" data-end="1903">4. Functionalism Without Naivety</h2>
<p data-start="1905" data-end="1963">Kempes’ functionalism is <em data-start="1930" data-end="1935">not</em> “life is just computation.”</p>
<p data-start="1965" data-end="1973">Instead:</p>
<ul data-start="1974" data-end="2164">
<li data-start="1974" data-end="2028">
<p data-start="1976" data-end="2028">Computation is <strong data-start="1991" data-end="2028">how optimization expresses itself</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2029" data-end="2081">
<p data-start="2031" data-end="2081">Physics determines <strong data-start="2050" data-end="2081">what computations are cheap</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2082" data-end="2164">
<p data-start="2084" data-end="2164">Materials are <strong data-start="2098" data-end="2164">historical accidents that instantiate those cheap computations</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2166" data-end="2177">That’s why:</p>
<ul data-start="2178" data-end="2288">
<li data-start="2178" data-end="2204">
<p data-start="2180" data-end="2204">Eyes evolve repeatedly</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2205" data-end="2247">
<p data-start="2207" data-end="2247">Multicellularity appears independently</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2248" data-end="2288">
<p data-start="2250" data-end="2288">Culture behaves like a living system</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2290" data-end="2372">Culture is not “like” life—it <strong data-start="2320" data-end="2326">is</strong> life running on neural and social substrates.</p>
<hr data-start="2374" data-end="2377">
<h2 data-start="2379" data-end="2429">5. Phase Transitions = Architectural Inventions</h2>
<p data-start="2431" data-end="2491">The “walls” Kempes talks about are <strong data-start="2466" data-end="2490">scaling catastrophes</strong>:</p>
<ul data-start="2493" data-end="2591">
<li data-start="2493" data-end="2511">
<p data-start="2495" data-end="2511">Diffusion limits</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2512" data-end="2541">
<p data-start="2514" data-end="2541">Energetic throughput limits</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2542" data-end="2563">
<p data-start="2544" data-end="2563">Coordination limits</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2564" data-end="2591">
<p data-start="2566" data-end="2591">Error accumulation limits</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2593" data-end="2618">Crossing a wall requires:</p>
<ul data-start="2619" data-end="2715">
<li data-start="2619" data-end="2663">
<p data-start="2621" data-end="2663">A <strong data-start="2623" data-end="2643">new architecture</strong>, not gradual tuning</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2664" data-end="2715">
<p data-start="2666" data-end="2715">Often an <strong data-start="2675" data-end="2693">external shock</strong> (e.g. Snowball Earth)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2717" data-end="2817">This is why evolution looks punctuated: the smooth curves are invisible at architectural resolution.</p>
<hr data-start="2819" data-end="2822">
<h2 data-start="2824" data-end="2874">6. Assembly Theory as an Anti-Earth Bias Filter</h2>
<p data-start="2876" data-end="2974">Assembly Theory is powerful not because it defines life, but because it defines <strong data-start="2956" data-end="2973">impossibility</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="2976" data-end="2988">Key insight:</p>
<ul data-start="2989" data-end="3123">
<li data-start="2989" data-end="3052">
<p data-start="2991" data-end="3052">Abiotic processes can only explore <strong data-start="3026" data-end="3052">shallow assembly depth</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3053" data-end="3123">
<p data-start="3055" data-end="3123">Living systems recursively reuse structure, exploding assembly depth</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3125" data-end="3179">That sharp cutoff is gold for astrobiology because it:</p>
<ul data-start="3180" data-end="3282">
<li data-start="3180" data-end="3224">
<p data-start="3182" data-end="3224">Does not care <em data-start="3196" data-end="3202">what</em> the object is made of</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3225" data-end="3282">
<p data-start="3227" data-end="3282">Only cares <strong data-start="3238" data-end="3282">how many historical decisions it encodes</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3284" data-end="3314">Life = deep, reusable history.</p>
<hr data-start="3316" data-end="3319">
<h2 data-start="3321" data-end="3380">7. The Error Threshold (Eigen’s Paradox) — The Hard Wall</h2>
<p data-start="3382" data-end="3447">This is the <strong data-start="3394" data-end="3446">most universal principle in the entire framework</strong>.</p>
<h3 data-start="3449" data-end="3465">The core law</h3>
<p data-start="3466" data-end="3537">Any information-bearing system has a maximum sustainable mutation rate:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>Q</mi><mi>L</mi></msup><mo>&gt;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>k</mi></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Q^L &gt; \frac{1}{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.0858em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">Q</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.8913em;"><span style="top: -3.113em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">L</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">&gt;</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 2.0074em; vertical-align: -0.686em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 1.3214em;"><span style="top: -2.314em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span><span style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span style="top: -3.677em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord">1</span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.686em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="3564" data-end="3570">Where:</p>
<ul data-start="3571" data-end="3671">
<li data-start="3571" data-end="3598">
<p data-start="3573" data-end="3598"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8778em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">Q</span></span></span></span> = fidelity per unit</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3599" data-end="3641">
<p data-start="3601" data-end="3641"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span></span> = length of the information string</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3642" data-end="3671">
<p data-start="3644" data-end="3671"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span></span> = selective advantage</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3673" data-end="3697">If mutation is too high:</p>
<ul data-start="3698" data-end="3780">
<li data-start="3698" data-end="3731">
<p data-start="3700" data-end="3731">Information cannot be preserved</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3732" data-end="3754">
<p data-start="3734" data-end="3754">Adaptation collapses</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3755" data-end="3780">
<p data-start="3757" data-end="3780">Selection becomes noise</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="3782" data-end="3819">Why this is substrate-independent</h3>
<p data-start="3820" data-end="3844">This applies equally to:</p>
<ul data-start="3845" data-end="3931">
<li data-start="3845" data-end="3858">
<p data-start="3847" data-end="3858">RNA genomes</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3859" data-end="3883">
<p data-start="3861" data-end="3883">Neural representations</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3884" data-end="3895">
<p data-start="3886" data-end="3895">Languages</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3896" data-end="3912">
<p data-start="3898" data-end="3912">Cultural norms</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3913" data-end="3931">
<p data-start="3915" data-end="3931">AI model weights</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3933" data-end="3978">If change outpaces memory, <strong data-start="3960" data-end="3977">learning dies</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="3980" data-end="4026">This is the <em data-start="3992" data-end="3998">real</em> universal boundary of life.</p>
<hr data-start="4028" data-end="4031">
<h2 data-start="4033" data-end="4082">8. Ontogenic Hacking: How Life Cheats the Wall</h2>
<p data-start="4084" data-end="4167">Ontogenic hacking is how life <strong data-start="4114" data-end="4166">re-routes information around the error threshold</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="4169" data-end="4180">Instead of:</p>
<ul data-start="4181" data-end="4258">
<li data-start="4181" data-end="4217">
<p data-start="4183" data-end="4217">Increasing fidelity (hard, costly)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4218" data-end="4258">
<p data-start="4220" data-end="4258">Slowing mutation (limits adaptability)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4260" data-end="4273">Life invents:</p>
<ul data-start="4274" data-end="4457">
<li data-start="4274" data-end="4316">
<p data-start="4276" data-end="4316"><strong data-start="4276" data-end="4296">Multicellularity</strong> (somatic shielding)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4317" data-end="4363">
<p data-start="4319" data-end="4363"><strong data-start="4319" data-end="4338">Nervous systems</strong> (fast internal learning)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4364" data-end="4406">
<p data-start="4366" data-end="4406"><strong data-start="4366" data-end="4388">Culture &amp; language</strong> (external memory)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4407" data-end="4457">
<p data-start="4409" data-end="4457"><strong data-start="4409" data-end="4423">Technology</strong> (persistent exosomatic structure)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4459" data-end="4490">This is not “faster evolution.”</p>
<p data-start="4492" data-end="4529">It is <strong data-start="4498" data-end="4528">evolution escaping biology</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="4531" data-end="4554">Information moves from:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mtext>genes</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>bodies</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>brains</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>culture</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>artifacts</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{genes} \rightarrow \text{bodies} \rightarrow \text{brains} \rightarrow \text{culture} \rightarrow \text{artifacts}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.625em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">genes</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">bodies</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">brains</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">culture</span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">artifacts</span></span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="4683" data-end="4693">Each step:</p>
<ul data-start="4694" data-end="4814">
<li data-start="4694" data-end="4726">
<p data-start="4696" data-end="4726">Increases information capacity</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4727" data-end="4759">
<p data-start="4729" data-end="4759">Lowers effective mutation rate</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4760" data-end="4814">
<p data-start="4762" data-end="4814">Allows longer “genomes” (ideas, institutions, tools)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4816" data-end="4819">
<h2 data-start="4821" data-end="4857">9. The Big Picture (One Sentence)</h2>
<blockquote data-start="4859" data-end="5014">
<p data-start="4861" data-end="5014"><strong data-start="4861" data-end="5014">Life is a physics-constrained learning process that repeatedly invents new substrates to carry more information without crossing the error threshold.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p data-start="5016" data-end="5041">If you want, next we can:</p>
<ul data-start="5042" data-end="5304">
<li data-start="5042" data-end="5099">
<p data-start="5044" data-end="5099">Formalize this as a <strong data-start="5064" data-end="5099">scale-dependent learning theory</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="5100" data-end="5158">
<p data-start="5102" data-end="5158">Compare it directly to <strong data-start="5125" data-end="5158">free energy / Bayesian brains</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="5159" data-end="5225">
<p data-start="5161" data-end="5225">Map it onto <strong data-start="5173" data-end="5225">AI training dynamics and catastrophic forgetting</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="5226" data-end="5304">
<p data-start="5228" data-end="5304">Or connect it to <strong data-start="5245" data-end="5304">civilizational collapse as an error-threshold violation</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="5306" data-end="5348" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">Just say which direction you want to push.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="z-0 flex min-h-[46px] justify-start"><div class="touch:-me-2 touch:-ms-3.5 -ms-2.5 -me-1 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-y-4 p-1 select-none touch:w-[calc(100%+--spacing(3.5))] -mt-1 w-[calc(100%+--spacing(2.5))] duration-[1.5s] focus-within:transition-none hover:transition-none touch:pointer-events-auto pointer-events-none [mask-image:linear-gradient(to_right,black_33%,transparent_66%)] [mask-size:300%_100%] [mask-position:100%_0%] motion-safe:transition-[mask-position] group-hover/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-hover/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] group-focus-within/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-focus-within/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] has-data-[state=open]:pointer-events-auto has-data-[state=open]:[mask-position:0_0]" style="mask-position: 0% 0%;"><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Copy" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="copy-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-k5zux585.svg#ce3544" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></span></button><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Good response" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="good-response-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-k5zux585.svg#51753c" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></span></button><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Bad response" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="bad