<h3 data-start="300" data-end="342">E. Measurability and Empirical Proxies</h3>
<p data-start="344" data-end="677">While the formalism developed in this paper is abstract, it specifies observables that can be approximated empirically. The challenge is not conceptual indeterminacy, but instrumentation. This section outlines how the principal quantities introduced—coherence potential, semantic entropy, and propagation flow—may be operationalized.</p>
<p data-start="679" data-end="1137">Coherence potential <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Φ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\Phi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord">Φ</span></span></span></span> may be approximated by measures of internal consistency and predictability. In textual systems, these include perplexity under a reference language model, stability of topic distributions across time, or invariance of citation networks under perturbation. In legal or institutional systems, coherence may be proxied by reversal rates, variance in adjudication outcomes, or divergence between stated policy and executed procedure.</p>
<p data-start="1139" data-end="1620">Semantic entropy <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span></span></span></span> admits multiple operationalizations depending on domain. In document corpora, entropy may be approximated by lexical diversity normalized by corpus size, growth in unresolved contradictions, or divergence between parallel interpretations. In repositories, technical debt metrics, unresolved conflicts, and test failures function as direct entropy indicators. Importantly, entropy here is not mere diversity; it is uncontrolled diversity that erodes identity.</p>
<p data-start="1622" data-end="1988">Propagation flow <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mover accent="true"><mi>v</mi><mo>⃗</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\vec{v}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.714em;"></span><span class="mord accent"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.714em;"><span style="top: -3em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">v</span></span><span style="top: -3em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="accent-body" style="left: -0.2077em;"><span class="overlay" style="height: 0.714em; width: 0.471em;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="0.471em" height="0.714em" viewBox="0 0 471 714" preserveAspectRatio="xMinYMin" style="width: 0.471em;"><path d="M377 20c0-5.333 1.833-10 5.5-14S391 0 397 0c4.667 0 8.667 1.667 12 5
3.333 2.667 6.667 9 10 19 6.667 24.667 20.333 43.667 41 57 7.333 4.667 11
10.667 11 18 0 6-1 10-3 12s-6.667 5-14 9c-28.667 14.667-53.667 35.667-75 63
-1.333 1.333-3.167 3.5-5.5 6.5s-4 4.833-5 5.5c-1 .667-2.5 1.333-4.5 2s-4.333 1
-7 1c-4.667 0-9.167-1.833-13.5-5.5S337 184 337 178c0-12.667 15.667-32.333 47-59
H213l-171-1c-8.667-6-13-12.333-13-19 0-4.667 4.333-11.333 13-20h359
c-16-25.333-24-45-24-59z"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> corresponds to rates and directions of semantic transmission. Observable proxies include citation velocity, commit frequency, policy enactment rates, or information diffusion patterns across networks. Directionality matters: coherent systems exhibit channelized flows, while collapsing systems exhibit isotropic or turbulent propagation.</p>
<p data-start="1990" data-end="2281">These proxies allow the construction of empirical phase diagrams. Systems may be tracked over time to identify approach toward or retreat from semantic error thresholds. While current measurement techniques are coarse, the framework specifies what improved instruments should aim to capture.</p>
<h3 data-start="2283" data-end="2318">F. Scaling Laws and System Size</h3>
<p data-start="2320" data-end="2699">The RSVP formulation predicts nontrivial scaling behavior as semantic systems grow. Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span></span> denote a characteristic linear scale of the system, such as population size, document count, or spatial extent. Diffusion terms in the RSVP equations scale as <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L^{-2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8141em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.8141em;"><span style="top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">−</span><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, while entropy production associated with uncontrolled interaction typically scales superlinearly with system size.</p>
<p data-start="2701" data-end="3093">As a result, maintaining semantic viability at larger scales requires either increased coherence coupling, stricter boundary conditions, or deeper hierarchical partitioning. This prediction aligns with empirical observations: large institutions develop layered bureaucracies, formalized procedures, and rigid architectures not as pathologies, but as adaptive responses to scaling constraints.</p>
<p data-start="3095" data-end="3362">Failure to introduce such constraints leads to abrupt collapse rather than gradual degradation. This explains the historical prevalence of sudden institutional breakdowns and linguistic fragmentation following periods of rapid expansion or technological acceleration.</p>
<h3 data-start="3364" data-end="3417">G. Uniqueness and Robustness of Semantic Identity</h3>
<p data-start="3419" data-end="3742">A final concern is whether semantic identity is uniquely defined or whether multiple inequivalent identities may coexist. In the information-geometric framework, identity corresponds to basins of attraction rather than points. Multiple basins may exist, corresponding to divergent but internally coherent semantic lineages.</p>
<p data-start="3744" data-end="4108">This multiplicity does not undermine the theory. On the contrary, it provides a formal account of speciation in semantic space. Forked repositories, schisms in religious traditions, and splinter political movements correspond to bifurcations of identity basins under perturbation. Viability depends on whether each basin independently satisfies closure conditions.</p>
<p data-start="4110" data-end="4403">Robustness is similarly contextual. Systems with broad, shallow basins tolerate more variation but risk drift. Systems with narrow, deep basins maintain identity rigidly but are vulnerable to rare shocks. These tradeoffs are not moral failings; they are structural properties of semantic life.</p>
