<p data-start="228" data-end="307">When they occur near the right margin, TeX has nowhere legal to break the line.</p>
<p data-start="309" data-end="437">Below are <strong data-start="319" data-end="356">clean, academically correct fixes</strong>, followed by a <strong data-start="372" data-end="411">recommended fully corrected passage</strong> you can drop in verbatim.</p>
<hr data-start="439" data-end="442">
<h2 data-start="444" data-end="473">Why this happens (briefly)</h2>
<ul data-start="475" data-end="631">
<li data-start="475" data-end="518">
<p data-start="477" data-end="518">Parentheses create a non-breakable group.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="519" data-end="584">
<p data-start="521" data-end="584">Inline math inside parentheses becomes a single horizontal box.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="585" data-end="631">
<p data-start="587" data-end="631">Long prose + no breakpoints → overfull hbox.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="633" data-end="674">This is expected behavior, not a mistake.</p>
<hr data-start="676" data-end="679">
<h2 data-start="681" data-end="712">Best-practice fixes (ranked)</h2>
