<h3 data-start="876" data-end="908">Why this is the <em data-start="896" data-end="903">right</em> form</h3>
<ul data-start="910" data-end="1178">
<li data-start="910" data-end="980">
<p data-start="912" data-end="980">No inline math inside parentheses → LaTeX can break lines naturally.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="981" data-end="1059">
<p data-start="983" data-end="1059">Each symbol is introduced grammatically → clearer for readers and reviewers.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1060" data-end="1178">
<p data-start="1062" data-end="1178">Terminology is now consistent with earlier sections (“propagation field,” “coherence potential,” “entropy density”).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1180" data-end="1263">If you want, the next step I strongly recommend is a <strong data-start="1233" data-end="1262">global normalization pass</strong>:</p>
<ul data-start="1265" data-end="1482">
<li data-start="1265" data-end="1355">
<p data-start="1267" data-end="1355">Replace <em data-start="1275" data-end="1282">every</em> remaining <code data-start="1293" data-end="1301">(\Phi)</code>, <code data-start="1303" data-end="1313">(\vec v)</code>, <code data-start="1315" data-end="1320">(S)</code>, <code data-start="1322" data-end="1332">(\theta)</code> pattern automatically.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1356" data-end="1427">
<p data-start="1358" data-end="1427">Ensure each symbol is introduced once per section, then used fluidly.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1428" data-end="1482">
<p data-start="1430" data-end="1482">Catch any remaining Markdown-era commas inside math.</p>
</li>
</ul>
